  "title": "GPLv3",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "da229c7000cf352d9d34e975c9aadf84",
      "text": "The GPLv3 is the third version of the [[GNU General Public License]]. It comes in two flavours the plain GPLv3 and the [[AGPL]] (Affero GPL). Both licenses were officially released on 29 June 2007 - [http://www.gnu.org/licenses/quick-guide-gplv3.en.html gnu.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c49a52a126530686",
      "text": "# Changes"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "30970d28e6253ea6",
      "text": "According to Stallman, the most important changes are in relation to [[Software Patents]], [[Free Software License Compatibility]], the [[Definition of Source Code]], and hardware restrictions on software modification ([[Tivoization]]) - [http://www.freesoftwaremagazine.com/articles/interview_with_richard_stallman freesoftwaremagazine.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6441cb416c57489a",
      "text": "Other changes relate to internationalization, how license violations are handled, and how additional permissions can be granted by the copyright holder."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7fffc581fc181940a099995c3a71bb2d",
      "text": "It also adds a provision that \"strips\" Digital Rights Management (DRM) of its legal value, so people can break anything a court might recognize as DRM on GPL software without breaking laws like the [[DMCA]] - [https://www.gnu.org/licenses/quick-guide-gplv3.html#neutralizing-laws-that-prohibit-free-software-but-not-forbidding-drm gnu.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "6a34afa2d3d7c5e52bb0d3cdff3aaeb2",
      "text": "<div style='padding: 12px; background:#eee; width:96%; align=centered;'>\n<a href='https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Stallman_GPLv3_launch_MIT_060116.jpg' target='_blank'>\n<img style='display:block; margin:auto; width:100%;'\nsrc='https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Stallman_GPLv3_launch_MIT_060116.jpg/420px-Stallman_GPLv3_launch_MIT_060116.jpg '>\n</a>\n\n<p class=caption>\n[[Richard Stallman]] at the launch of the first draft of the GNU GPLv3. MIT, Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA. To his right is Columbia Law Professor [[Eben Moglen]], chairman of the Software Freedom Law Center\n[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Stallman_GPLv3_launch_MIT_060116.jpg - wikimedia]\n</p></div>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "20c600e1bbc0cc35",
      "text": "# Affero GPLv3"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "862128429b7449d87ceca172ef50bf54",
      "text": "Also, early drafts of GPLv3 let licensors add an Affero ([[Affero General Public License]]) -like requirement that would have plugged the ''ASP ([[Application Service Provider]]) loophole in the GPL'' - [http://opensource.org/node/152 opensource.org] and [http://www.fsf.org/licensing/licenses/index.html fsf.org]: "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "75c7d981569f985b",
      "text": "<blockquote>We recommend that developers consider using the GNU AGPL for any software which will commonly be run over a network.</blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a1402bd8d117cc71",
      "text": "As there were concerns expressed about the administrative costs of checking code for this additional requirement, it was decided to keep the GPL and the Affero license separated - [https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-faq.html#SeparateAffero gnu.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aa355bc8729695b834b86dcbe6f45cfd",
      "text": "GPLv3 improves compatibility with several open source software licenses such as Apache License, version 2.0, and the GNU Affero General Public License, which GPLv2 could not be combined with.[http://www.techlawforum.net/post.cfm/gpl-3-overview GPL 3 Overview] But on the downside, GPLv3 software can only be combined and share code with GPLv2 software if the used GPLv2 license has the optional ''\"or later\"'' clause and the software is upgraded to GPLv3. While the \"GPLv2 or any later version\" clause is considered by FSF as the most common form of licensing GPLv2 software,[https://www.gnu.org/licenses/quick-guide-gplv3.html#new-compatible-licenses A Quick Guide to GPLv3 – GNU Project – Free Software Foundation (FSF)] for example [[Toybox]] developer Rob Landley described it as a ''lifeboat clause''.[http://landley.net/talks/celf-2013.txt CELF 2013 Toybox talk] Software projects licensed with the optional ''\"or later\"'' clause include the [[GNU Project]], while a prominent example without the clause is the Linux kernel.<ref name=\"linuxlicense\"/>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5858d649866981cb",
      "text": "# Process of Drafting"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a0906513a0d9d90ca48410b7b8cbd107",
      "text": "In late 2005, the [[Free Software Foundation]] (FSF) announced work on version 3 of the GPL ([[GPLv3]]). On 16 January 2006, the first \"discussion draft\" of GPLv3 was published, and the public consultation began. The public consultation was originally planned for nine to fifteen months but finally stretched to eighteen months with four drafts being published. The official [[GPLv3]] was released by FSF on 29 June 2007. GPLv3 was written by [[Richard Stallman]], with legal counsel from [[Eben Moglen]] and the [[Software Freedom Law Center]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1c3f0555f636467591b151aa944247a8",
      "text": "The public consultation process was coordinated by the Free Software Foundation with assistance from Software Freedom Law Center, [[Free Software Foundation Europe]],[http://fsfeurope.org/projects/gplv3/ GPLv3: Drafting version 3 of the GNU General Public License] and other free software groups. Comments were collected from the public via the gplv3.fsf.org web portal.[http://gplv3.fsf.org/comments/gplv3-draft-4.html gplv3.fsf.org comments for discussion draft 4] That portal runs purpose-written software called stet ([[stet (software)]])."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f5262e22bad3fc2930ace4d5e0d9958d",
      "text": "During the public consultation process, 962 comments were submitted for the first draft.[http://gplv3.fsf.org/comments/gplv3-draft-1 gplv3.fsf.org comments for draft 1] By the end, a total of 2,636 comments had been submitted.[http://gplv3.fsf.org/comments/gplv3-draft-2.html gplv3.fsf.org comments for draft 2][http://gplv3.fsf.org/comments/gplv3-draft-3 gplv3.fsf.org comments for draft 3][http://gplv3.fsf.org/comments/gplv3-draft-4.html gplv3.fsf.org comments for draft 4]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9927a0a62035e366e644b3d92b036f58",
      "text": "The third draft was released on 28 March 2007. This draft included language intended to prevent patent-related agreements like the controversial Microsoft-Novell patent agreement ([[Microsoft-Novell agreement]]) and restricts the anti-tivoization clauses to a legal definition of a \"User\" or \"consumer product\". It also explicitly removed the section on \"Geographical Limitations\", whose probable removal had been announced at the launch of the public consultation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f5aa81cf5c2e51ef01d42edd6750fbe7",
      "text": "The fourth discussion draft,[ ] which was the last, was released on 31 May 2007. It introduced [[Apache License]] version 2.0 compatibility (prior versions are incompatible), clarified the role of outside contractors, and made an exception to avoid the perceived problems of a Microsoft–Novell style agreement, saying in Section 11 paragraph 6 that:"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "e3f1e0e62cc574885ff0acd85c3cd632",
      "text": "<blockquote>\nYou may not convey a covered work if you are a party to an arrangement with a third party that is in the business of distributing software, under which you make payment to the third party based on the extent of your activity of conveying the work, and under which the third party grants, to any of the parties who would receive the covered work from you, a discriminatory patent license [...]\n</blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ace79ad7a334646784b1b465f68fdfc",
      "text": "This aims to make future such deals ineffective. The license is also meant to cause Microsoft to extend the patent licenses it grants to Novell customers for the use of GPLv3 software to ''all'' users of that GPLv3 software; this is possible only if Microsoft is legally a \"conveyor\" of the GPLv3 software."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "aeeb19e6c07781a1",
      "text": "# Linux Still Uses GPLv2"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7b1fba599b9a173fc3e69d231f066385",
      "text": "Others, notably some high-profile developers of the [[Linux kernel]], for instance [[Linus Torvalds]], [[Greg Kroah-Hartman]] and Andrew Morton ([[Andrew Morton (computer programmer)]]), commented to the mass media and made public statements about their objections to parts of discussion drafts 1 and 2.<ref name=\"kerneldevelopers2006\"/> The kernel developers referred to GPLv3 draft clauses regarding DRM ([[Digital rights management]])/[[Tivoization]], patents and \"additional restrictions\" and warned a [[Balkanisation]] of the \"Open Source Universe\".[ ][http://www.linuxjournal.com/node/1000100 A fight against evil or a fight for attention?] Linus Torvalds, who decided to not adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel,<ref name=\"linuxlicense\"/> reiterated his criticism even years later.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PaKIZ7gJlRU Linus Torvalds says GPL v3 violates everything that GPLv2 stood for] [[Debconf]] 2014, [[Portland, Oregon]] (accessed 11 March 2015)</ref><ref name=\"torvaldsgpl\"/>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7521b17d6e4ac059e0b0f01931277a2a",
      "text": "The final version of the license text was published on 29 June 2007.[https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl.html GNU General Public License]"
    }
